Machine Learning for Kids Walkthrough — Caption File
Module 4 | Adjust timestamps to match final video render.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hey! In this walkthrough, I'm going to show you
step-by-step how to use a free tool

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.000
called Machine Learning for Kids
to train your own AI model —

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.000
and then test it out.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
It takes about 15 minutes
and you don't need to install anything.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Let's go!

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
First, open your browser and go to:
machinelearningforkids.co.uk

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
You'll see this homepage.
Click "Get started."

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
You can log in with a school account,
or use "Try it without registering" to jump straight in.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Once you're in, click "Add a new project."

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Give your project a name.
Let's call it "Animal Classifier."

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
For the type, select "images" —
we're going to train it to recognize images.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Then click "Create."

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Boom — your project exists!
Click on it to open it.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
You'll see three stages:
Train, Learn & Test, and Make.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
We'll go through all three.
Click "Train."

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
This is where you add your training data.
Click "Add new label"

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
and type your first category.
Let's do "cat."

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Now add another label: "dog."

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Now we need examples.
Click "Add example" under cat.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
You can take a picture with your camera,
or upload an image from your computer.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Add at least 10 examples per category —
the more the better!

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Mix up your angles, backgrounds, and lighting.
The AI needs variety to learn well.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Go back and click "Learn & Test."
Then click the big "Train new machine learning model" button.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
This sends your labeled images to a cloud server
that trains your model.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.000
It usually takes 1–3 minutes.
You'll see a progress bar.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:56.000
While you're waiting — this is exactly what we talked about
in the animated video!

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Data going in, model being trained, accuracy coming out.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.000
It's done! You can see your model's accuracy.
Now let's test it.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Click "Test your model."

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Show it a cat picture — or take a photo.
Look at that —

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
your AI made a prediction!
It says "cat" with 87% confidence.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Let's try a dog.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Nice! It got that right too.
Try a tricky one —

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:46.000
a blurry photo, or one with weird lighting.
See how confident it is.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
The third stage is Make —
this is where you can take your model into a real project

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:12.000
in Scratch or a web app.
If you're doing the extension activity,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:18.000
click "Scratch 3" to open a Scratch editor
with your AI model built right in!

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:25.000
You can see there are special blocks just for your model.
You could build a game where a sprite reacts differently

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
when it sees a cat vs. a dog!

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:47.000
That's it! You just trained and tested
your own machine learning model.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
If you want to make it smarter,
go back to Train and add more examples.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:00.000
More data, better model —
that's the golden rule of machine learning.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Now go take the Module 4 quiz
and show off what you know. You've got this!
